    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Peristylus timorensis are used primarily for their medicinal properties. Infusion is a preparation of the plant's leaves and flowers in hot water, typically used for its antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects. Tincture is an alcohol-based extraction of the plant's roots, often used for its antimicrobial properties and as a digestive aid. Decoction involves boiling the plant's roots in water to release its active compounds, commonly used for its diuretic and expectorant properties. Peristylus timorensis salve is a topical preparation of the plant's roots and leaves in a fatty oil base, often used to treat skin irritations and wounds, while tea is a preparation of the plant's leaves in hot water, used for its calming and soothing effects.",
